So, addressing FuzzyBoots, I removed the compulsion to look, and adjusted the containment procedures accordingly (no need for a large room when a small room will do).

On the Incident Report, I went back through and un-redacted the researchers' names, which accounted for about 90% of the redaction. I'm hoping it improves it - my logic behind the Incident Report was trying to , something that I was initially concerned this SCP did poorly (it's a common comment I've gotten from people on my writing in the past). I'm hoping that helped.

I changed the picture caption; hopefully this works better. If need be, I can remove the picture entirely - there wasn't a picture to begin with, I added one because I thought it helped. I've been wrong before.

I like the suggestion about the D-class testing. I've put a line about a proposal for exactly that sort of research in (it'd be on hold pending the resumption of research into 1215).

On Footnote 2, I'm inclined to keep it in. When I was doing real-world research into the Peri Logismon and the origins of the seven deadly sins for this, I discovered the quote which is in the footnote. It struck me as just too perfect for the purposes of writing an SCP - it read just as though Evagrius had written in one of his own  warnings, albeit in the Medieval Greek prose of a monk as opposed to detached Modern English of a Foundation SCP report. Rather eerie coming across it, actually. So, I decided to put it in.

As I've stated repeatedly before, this is my first SCP and I'm open to any suggestions people have.







