Well, Evagrius did write the real-world Peri Logismon as a guide for understanding and learning to overcome temptation (as indicated in the first footnote), so I disagree with that it is . I'm trying to suggest, without out-right stating, that Evagrius intended 1215 as a tool for readers to overcome their temptations so that they could live in accordance with God's wishes. Since very few people in the 4th century were literate, making the manuscript affect people who merely looked at it would allow it to help more people than if it were simply limited to those who could actually read written words.

As to the effects being obvious, while the Phase III effects are extreme and obvious, the time scale and the description of what occurred in the incident report were attempts at demonstrating how the effects are subtle to begin with and only slowly escalate and spiral out of control.

I also am trying to indicate that there may be a  for the effects, possibly by overcoming the temptations, but that for whatever reason the Foundation research teams haven't figured it out yet.

So, I had put some method behind the madness, but I was trying to avoid putting it into the text of the SCP itself - less being more, and all that - but I'm open to suggestions on how to add these to the article without de-mystifying it too much.







